description.narrative:
1.	Inventory of the assessment methodologies and tools currently used (or under development) by DWA partners E-Sus elements and classify them in their focus on/relevance of particular WASH aspects and approaches (i.eRAIN’s RWHT; PRACTICA’s DWDST; WASTE’s SDST, etc.);
2.	Inventory of existing CATs and assessment on usability for the currently to be developed CAT; 
3.	Identify how to make the connection between the CAT and other methodologies and tools, i.e. particular the DWDST, i.e. how a user can easily ‘move’ from the one tool to the next. 
4.	Review of the internal and external inventory and defining of applicable and non-applicable elements / tools, regarding the content and quality of the ecological, hydrological and socio-economic aspects relevant for the CAT;
5.	Decide on the elements/criteria to be part of the CAT and its form and parallel its linkage to the DWDST.
6.	Discuss the inventory of steps 1 to 5 with relevant DWA partners to assess usability in their planning processes. Adjust standards/elements based on the feedback provided by DWA partners.
7.	Decide on the form of the CAT and develop the final CAT.
